By: David Hoffman, Jonas Moros, and Sully Billingsley¶

1. Business Understanding¶

Bitcoin is the longest running and most well-known cryptocurrency on the market. This dataset is comprised of minute to minute updates of OHLC (Open, High, Low, Close), Volume in BTC and indicated currency, and weighted bitcoin price from the period of January 2012 to March of 2021. The first collumn of each row contains a Unix timestamp which represents when the remainder of the datapoints in that row were collected.

This data was collected in order to understand various trends within the Bitcoin market and is used by many traders to train the machine learning algorithms that they use to automate the entirety of their daily crypocurrency trading. Similarly to these cryptocurrency day traders, our prediction task is to predict whether or not the price of bitcoin will rise or fall on any given day.

If we are able to generate a meaningful conclusion from this data the results we obtain could prove incredibly useful for nearly any third party from large public corporations to small private investors. Given the ease with which Bitcoin can be traded on public markets such as Coinbase or Robinhood, anyone who has access to these applications could use our conclusions to guide their bitcoin trades in a profitable direction.

In order for our research to be useful for our needs as well as the needs of the general consumer, our conclusions would need to have at least an 80% accuracy rating. We believe it is impossible to be 100% accurate with these predictions given the incredible volatility of the market we are trying to predict; however, if we are able to reach an 80% accuracy rating our predictions would start to give us a competitive edge within the market. With 80% accuracy we would expect to accurately predict most of the big swings which are where we would do the majority of our more high-risk buys and sells. Contrarily, we would expect the majority of our 20% error to come from days that were not predicted to move much either way and went slighly up when we expected it to go down or vice versa. On these days we would plan on holding our assets anyway and therefore would hardly feel the negative impact of a prediction error.

Dataset URL: https://www.kaggle.com/mczielinski/bitcoin-historical-data

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

# load bitcoin historical dataset into pandas 
df = pd.read_csv('/content/drive/MyDrive/SMU/Fall 2021/ML/Lab1/bitstampUSD_1-min_data_2012-01-01_to_2021-03-31.csv')

df['Timestamp'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Timestamp'],unit='s' )

df.set_index("Timestamp",inplace=True)



    















The code above reads in our main dataset and stores it in our ititial dataframe.  Additionally, we convert the Timestamp feature from a Unix timestamp to a datetime timestamp which will enhance overall readability as well as make this feature easier to work with in the future.













In [ ]:



    


day_df = pd.DataFrame()
day_df['Open'] = df['Open'].resample('D').first()
day_df['High'] = df['High'].resample('D').max()
day_df['Low'] = df['Low'].resample('D').min()
day_df['Close'] = df['Close'].resample('D').last()
day_df['Volume_(BTC)'] = df['Volume_(BTC)'].resample('D').sum()
day_df['Volume_(USD)'] = df['Volume_(Currency)'].resample('D').sum()
day_df['VWP'] = df['Weighted_Price'].resample('D').mean()



    















Next, we created a new dataframe called 'daydf' which takes the minute-to-minute data held in our original dataframe and condenses it so that the data is now represented in a day-to-day format.  This is crucial given the massive size of our original dataset.  With the day-to-day data it will be much easier to manage and should give us easier and more meaningful visualizations.  For both the 'Open' and 'Close' features we took the first and last (respectively) value per day.  For the 'High' we took the maximum value per day and for the 'Low' we took the minimum.  Lastly, we summed the values for each day for both 'Volume(BTC)' and 'Volume_(USD)' and took the mean for 'VMP'.

day_df['dt'] = pd.to_datetime(day_df.index).date

In the code above we created an additional column called 'Day_Stats' which will track the overall performance during each time period by subtracting the opening price from the closing price resulting in the overall movement in price over the course of a single day.  We will treat this as categorical data and will later convert the numeric answer into a string which will define the day as either being 'Big Up', 'Small Up', 'No Change', 'Small Down', or 'Big Down'. In addition to the 'DayStats' categorical feature, 'Open', 'Close', 'High', and 'Low' will be very important features for our analysis as well.  We do not expect to find as useful of a correlation within the 'Volume(BTC)', 'Volume_(Currency)', and 'Weighted_Price' features although we still will try to gain as much insight as possible from all of the different features included in our dataframe.













In [ ]:



    


# Numerical Data in the 'Day_Stats' column is converted into a string that enhances readibility
day_df.loc[day_df['Day_Stats'] > 7.5, 'DS_categorical'] = 'Big Up' 
day_df.loc[(day_df['Day_Stats'] <= 7.5) & (day_df['Day_Stats'] > 1), 'DS_categorical'] = 'Small Up' 
day_df.loc[(day_df['Day_Stats'] <= 1) & (day_df['Day_Stats'] >= -1), 'DS_categorical'] = 'No Change' 
day_df.loc[(day_df['Day_Stats'] < -1) & (day_df['Day_Stats'] >= -7.5), 'DS_categorical'] = 'Small Down' 
day_df.loc[day_df['Day_Stats'] < -7.5, 'DS_categorical'] = 'Big Down'

From this function we can see the number of null values (NaN) within our dataset.  Originally, our dataset contained a large number of null values; however, many of these holes were smoothed over during the data consolodation step in the section above. During consolodation we decided that elimination would be a better solution than imputation in order to smooth out our data and make our analysis easier as the sheer number of missing data points would make it nearly impossible to impute these values in an effective manner.













In [ ]:



    


# Remove rows where all of the values are NaN in the price columns because this means there is no meaningful infomration and is also nonsensical to forward fill a whole day
day_df_eliminated = day_df.dropna(subset=['Open', 'High','Low','Close'])

# Forward fill on chain stats because those were sampled on a frequency of every third day
day_df_eliminated.ffill(inplace=True)

# print number of rows in day_df_imputed
print('Length of updated dataset:', day_df_eliminated.shape[0])

# Print the number of rows that have been deleted by the elimination
print('Number of rows deleted by elimination operation:', day_df.shape[0]-day_df_eliminated.shape[0])

f, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2)

In the first graph, we plot the correlation between the hash rate or the amount of computing power used on a given day with the closing price of each day.  From this, we can see a pretty strong correlation between these two variables as the hash rate seems to increase as the closing value of Bitcoin increased.  This makes sense because Bitcoin is designed in such a way that the cost of mining an individual Bitcoin increases as market volume increases.  As it becomes more difficult to mine bitcoin, the hash rate will increase and the price of bitcoin must rise in order to make ensure mining is still profitable when the marginal amount of bitcoin a miner makes over time is reduced.


In the second graph, we plotted the correlation between the hash rate and the overall volume of Bitcoin that is traded on a given day.  From this it is fairly evident that there is not a major correlation between these two features as the majority of our data points exhist to the left of the graph with the volume staying relatively the same as hash rate goes up.  Additionally, we can see that hash rate does not go up as volume goes up as we explore more of our data points to th right of the main cluster.


From this analysis, we can determine that hash rate has a much stronger correlation with price than it does with volume showing that price may be a great indicator for the network requirements of the system and vice versa.  The Spearman's coefficient of the hash rate graph is nearly 1 showing a very high correlation while the coefficeint of the volume graph is less than .2.

mapper_w_onchain = umap.UMAP(n_neighbors=10,min_dist=0.01,metric='correlation').fit(day_df[['Volume_(BTC)','n_transact', 'diff', 'hash']].to_numpy())



    













In [ ]:



    


umap.plot.points(mapper_w_onchain, labels=np.array(day_df['DS_categorical']))



    















    
Out[ ]:








<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7f098e98abd0>










    




























The Dataset created has two areas of data that correlate better with each other, so two sets of UMAP were performed because when it was performed on the whole dataset, no interesting separations were present in 2 dimensions. In the first plot, the different groups can clearly be identified and seem to exist in a similar area in that phase space but can still be differentiated. The separation can be visualized by a gradient in color going from blue to yellow to red. This tells us that if a prediction model were to be run on this dataset, it could possibly benefit from reducing the price and volume data to only 2-dimensions. The second plot now attempts to reduce the on-chain statistics to 2 dimensions. No meaningful separation can be determined from the plot. As opposed to the first plot, there is no clear grouping of the classes to show a dimensionality reduction would prove useful. This logic stems from applications where things like clothing are classified from images. Some pixels dont provide completely unique information and through grouping through neighbors in higher-dimensional space, the features can be compressed to a lower dimension space.


UMAP utilizes graph theory to reduce a higher-dimensional graph to a lower dimensional graph. The graph concept plays an integral role by providing connection points in whatever dimensional space it is in. Connections are created by determining the number of neighbors allowed and the distance between neighbors. As connections are made, those connected are then mapped down to the required dimensions based on the space where the neighbors are. This then shows us that if our classes in our UMAP examples do not closely group, then dimensionality reduction can not prove useful because the information is not related enough to be condensed.
